subSubSection.paragraph:
Head (
Fig. 19A
), covered with sparse setiferous punctures; setae produced from inside punctures (
Fig. 20A
); frontoclypeal suture bisinuate, middle portion narrow, about one fourth width of clypeus; labrum and clypeus convex and furnished with setae; length of clypeus longer than that of labrum. Anterior margin of clypeus weakly lined (
Fig. 18A
). Canthus small, obtusely triangular with apex rounded, furnished with a few setiferous punctures. Apex of mandible bifurcate and furnished with one large tooth apically on inner margin; lateral angles furnished with setae (
Fig. 18D
). Antennae weakly clavate; segments short, except for first, third and fourth which are long and slender, eleventh pointed; all segments setous, fifth through eleventh with smaller, denser setae (
Fig. 18C
).

Pronotum (
Fig. 18A
, 
19B
) with blunt lateral tubercles, strongly tapered towards base; lateral basal angles weakly swollen; surface regularly convex, densely covered with coarse setiferous punctures (
Fig. 19B
); distance between punctures 0.5–2 times their own diameter, sparser on posterior half of longitudinal median portion and posterior half of lateral portions. Setae produced from inside punctures (
Fig. 19B
).

Elytra long, leaving apex of pygidium exposed, moderately vaulted in lateral view; lateral sides subparallel; surface with reticulate coriaceous microsculpture, irregularly covered with dense setiferous punctures, punctures coarsely separated by 0.5–3 times their diameter; setae produced anterior to punctures, the posterior two-thirds of each puncture deep (
Fig. 20D
); lateral grooves complete from elytral base to apex; sutural grooves ambiguous on elytral base; basal areas of elytra weakly convex on either side of suture; humerus protruding anteriorly; epipleuron narrow. Scutellum trapezoidal, with setae.Disc of mesoventrite rugose; process short, furnished with setiferous punctures (
Fig. 18B
, 
19C
). Mesepisternum furnished with setiferous punctures, except near suture separating it from mesepimeron (
Fig. 18B
, 
19C
). Surface of metaventrite with reticulate coriaceous microsculpture (
Fig. 20C
), central area sparsely covered with setiferous punctures, becoming denser on lateral portions, setae produced anterior to shallow punctures (
Fig. 20C
); posterior margin of mid coxal insertion markedly punctate. Surface of sternites sparsely covered with setiferous punctures. In male, posterior margin of 7th sternite evenly curved (
Fig. 19D
). In female, apex of pygidium weakly concave; posterior margin of 7th sternite straight, but bisinuate on central portion (
Fig. 18E
).

Male genitalia as shown in 
Fig. 21
A–F: 8th sternite furnished with setae, short, oblique anteriorly, membrane and sclerotized portion narrow ventrally, allowing for downward extension (
Fig. 21E, F
); apex of spiculum three branched, central branch furnished with tiny setae (
Fig. 21D
); median struts of median lobe approximately 1.5 times as long as median lobe (
Fig. 21A
); apex of median lobe pointed (
Fig. 21B
), lateral side flattened (
Fig. 21A
); paramere well developed (
Fig. 21C
).
